### 8. Exception Handling â€” `ProcessOrder_EmptyOrder_ThrowsValidationError`

```csharp
try
{
    processor.ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.Fail("Expected an exception but none was thrown");
}
catch (ValidationException ex)
{
    Assert.AreEqual("Order must contain at least one item", ex.Message);
}
```

**Problem:** Manual try/catch obscures intent and risks silently swallowing unexpected exception types. If a different exception is thrown, the test reports as an unhandled error rather than a clear assertion failure.

**Fix:** Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (already used correctly in the clean test at line 159):

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_EmptyOrder_ThrowsValidationError()
{
    var processor = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory);
    var order = new Order();

    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ValidationException>(
        () => processor.ProcessOrder(order));

    Assert.AreEqual("Order must contain at least one item", ex.Message);
}
```

